{"source_key":"sha256-ea08d35f42d5530fbe92c80d4f5b27e9","record_index":959,"record_hash":"sha256:3774ab93941676bed65d26bbe4c3e5d3ac8f64cbdf00655e3d6182b435fcfae5","timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:12:40.589Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"{\"previous_status\":{\"completed\":\"Lane D call: **use a local persistent volume, one writer per repo, no network/object filesystem for the hot cache.** Lightest good path is Fly/Render/Railway volume. If AWS, use EC2/ECS/Fargate + EBS, not Lambda + EFS/S3.\\n\\n**Why**\\nGit and SQLite both want boring filesystem semantics.\\n\\n- Git repos are on-disk structures with objects, refs, packs, locks, and atomic-ish maintenance. Git’s own FAQ warns against cloud-syncing any part of a repo because file-by-file sync can corrupt refs/objects. [Git FAQ](https://git-scm.com/docs/gitfaq.html)\\n- `git gc` can corrupt or break a repo if it races another writer, so maintenance must run under the same repo lock. [git-gc docs](https://www.kernel.org/pub/software/scm/git/docs/git-gc.html)\\n- SQLite WAL explicitly does **not** work over network filesystems. [SQLite WAL](https://www.sqlite.org/wal.html)\\n- SQLite depends on filesystem locks; the docs call out network filesystems/NFS as especially risky when locks are buggy. [SQLite corruption docs](https://www.sqlite.org/howtocorrupt.html)\\n- S3 mount layers are not acceptable for Git/SQLite. AWS Mountpoint for S3 says it does not support file locking, symlinks, or modifying existing files. [AWS S3 Mountpoint](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html)\\n\\n**Recommended architecture**\\n\\n```text\\nAgent Trail API/service\\n  /data\\n    repos/github/<repo-id>.git\\n    locks/github/<repo-id>.lock\\n    db/agent-trail.sqlite\\n    snapshots/<snapshot-id>.json\\n    tmp/\\n```\\n\\nUse a **bare repo cache** per upstream repo if we can make `but-agentlog` accept bare repos cleanly. Git docs describe bare repos as the normal shape for exchanging histories, and `git clone --mirror` implies bare and maps all refs. [gitrepository-layout](https://git-scm.com/docs/gitrepository-layout/2.25.0), [git-clone](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-clone.html)\\n\\nFetch only what we need:\\n\\n```bash\\ngit fetch origin \\\\\\n  +refs/heads/<branch>:refs/heads/<branch> \\\\\\n  +refs/meta/*:refs/meta/*\\n```\\n\\nIf custom meta refs are unreliable through Pierre/code.storage, fetch from GitHub directly first and use Pierre later as an optimization.\\n\\n**Concurrency rule**\\n\\nOne exclusive lock per repo around:\\n\\n```text\\nfetch -> git-meta pull/materialize -> agentlog projection -> optional git maintenance\\n```\\n\\nAcross different repos, parallelize freely. Across the same repo, serialize. Also set `gc.auto=0` and run maintenance only inside that repo lock.\\n\\n**Backup rule**\\n\\nRepo cache is rebuildable. Don’t make it precious.\\n\\n- For SQLite, use SQLite backup API or `VACUUM INTO`, not raw `cp` of a live WAL DB. [SQLite backup API](https://sqlite.org/backup.html)\\n- For Git cache warm backups, use `git bundle` or clone/fetch under lock. Git docs explicitly discourage naive `cp -r` while the repo may be written. [git-bundle](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-bundle.html)\\n- Store final immutable projection JSON in object storage if useful. S3/R2/Tigris are fine for outputs, not for the working repo.\\n\\n**Hosting pick**\\n\\nUse **Fly Machine + Fly Volume** first. It’s local persistent storage mounted like a normal directory, with daily snapshots. [Fly volumes](https://fly.io/docs/volumes/overview/)\\n\\nRender and Railway are also fine. [Render disks](https://render.com/docs/disks), [Railway volumes](https://docs.railway.com/volumes)\\n\\nAWS is fine but heavier. If forced into AWS, pick **ECS/Fargate or EC2 + EBS**. EBS is durable block storage suitable for database-style frequent updates. [EBS docs](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/ebs/latest/userguide/ebs-volumes.html)\\n\\nSkip Lambda/serverless for this. Lambda `/tmp` is ephemeral and capped at 10 GB; Fargate ephemeral storage is bigger but still ephemeral. [Lambda ephemeral storage](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html), [Fargate ephemeral storage](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html)\\n\\nNo files edited.\"}}","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T16:12:40.589Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}